{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2489"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2489"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.7,0.12,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79105"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64457"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"1310"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11058"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42504"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79105"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman is seen by her psychiatrist for review of her paranoid schizophrenia, for which she takes risperidone 3mg PO BD. She was first treated with olanzapine following initial diagnosis at the age of 20, however this agent was switched to risperidone three months ago after she experienced troublesome weight gain from olanzapine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver this period, there has been no emergence of psychotic symptoms, however she has been feeling fatigued and complains that her periods have become irregular. She reports some mild breast tenderness, as well as nipple discharge. Subsequent investigations reveal a serum prolactin level of 1655mU/L (normal \u0026lt;750mU/L). The psychiatrist explains that her symptoms are likely a side-effect of her risperidone and that a further medication change might be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Switching to which one of the following medications would be suitable in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Aripiprazole","Clozapine","Paliperidone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is aripiprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has good control of her schizophrenia and there is no evidence of psychosis, however she appears to have recently developed hyperprolactinaemia, a common side-effect of risperidone treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyperprolactinaemia is a well-known adverse effect of many antipsychotic agents and is associated with a number of clinical consequences (both acute and chronic). These can include menstrual disturbances (oligomenorrhoea or amenorrhoea) in women, gynaecomastia in men, and breast tenderness, galactorrhoea, sexual dysfunction and increased risk of osteoporosis and fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe antipsychotic agents implicated in hyperprolactinaemia include all of the typical antipsychotics, as well as a small number of atypical antipsychotics including risperidone and palpiperidone. Most of the other atypical antipsychotics such as aripiprazole, olanzapine, quetiapine, ziprasidone and clozapine are not associated with elevation in serum prolactin levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAripiprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is a potent partial dopamine D2 agonist, acting as a functional antagonist at D2 receptors under hyperdopaminergic conditions, but conversely acting as a functional D2 receptor agonist under hypodopaminergic conditions. As a result of this, aripiprazole is not associated with elevated prolactin levels; in fact, the literature suggests it may even have a prolactin-lowering effect in some patients. This makes aripiprazole the most appropriate agent for this woman.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate because it is a typical antipsychotic agent and will also cause hyperprolactinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E is an atypical antipsychotic that is less likely to cause hyperprolactinaemia, but it is not as effective as aripiprazole in managing prolactin levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eclozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with hyperprolactinaemia, it is not indicated in this case. Clozapine would only be considered if her schizophrenia remained uncontrolled after trialling at least two antipsychotic agents. There is no suggestion that her schizophrenia symptoms were refractory to either of the agents she has been on (olanzapine and risperidone).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome evidence points towards an association between \u003Cstrong\u003Epaliperidone\u003C/strong\u003E and elevated prolactin levels, making this agent a less appropriate substitute.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aripiprazole is a satisfactory second-line schizophrenia treatment for patients who are experiencing troublesome side-effects with risperidone.","Hyperprolactinaemia is a common side effect of certain antipsychotics, including risperidone, and can lead to symptoms such as menstrual irregularities and galactorrhoea.","Aripiprazole, an atypical antipsychotic, is less likely to cause hyperprolactinaemia compared to other antipsychotics."],"references":["Shim JC, Shin JG, Kelly DL, Jung DU, Seo YS, Liu KH, Shon JH, Conley RR. Adjunctive treatment with a dopamine partial agonist, aripiprazole, for antipsychotic-induced hyperprolactinemia: a placebo-controlled trial. Am J Psychiatry. 2007 Sep;164(9):1404-10. doi: 10.1176/appi.ajp.2007.06071075. PMID: 17728426. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17728426/","Mittal S, Prasad S, Ghosh A. Antipsychotic-induced hyperprolactinaemia: case studies and review. Postgrad Med J. 2018 Apr;94(1110):226-229. doi: 10.1136/postgradmedj-2017-135221. Epub 2017 Nov 9. PMID: 29122927. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29122927/","Byerly MJ, Marcus RN, Tran QV, Eudicone JM, Whitehead R, Baker RA. Effects of aripiprazole on prolactin levels in subjects with schizophrenia during cross-titration with risperidone or olanzapine: analysis of a randomized, open-label study. Schizophr Res. 2009 Feb;107(2-3):218-22. doi: 10.1016/j.schres.2008.09.019. Epub 2008 Nov 26. PMID: 19038534. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19038534/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64457"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2489"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64457"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:00:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:01:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79105"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49: